The article explores how Rust implements the `fetch_max` atomic operation, triggered by the author's curiosity during a job interview. It begins tracing this operation's implementation through multiple abstraction layers, starting with the clean Rust syntax (`high_score.fetch_max(200, Ordering::Relaxed)`) and proceeding through macro expansion. The investigation aims to understand how Rust provides this as a built-in operation when many other languages require explicit compare-and-swap (CAS) loops, especially since common architectures like x86-64 don't have native atomic max instructions.

## Key Insight
While most languages require developers to implement atomic max operations using explicit compare-and-swap loops, Rust abstracts this complexity away with a simple `fetch_max` method that handles all the concurrency challenges behind the scenes.
